The paper proposes a novel end-to-end learning scheme for predicting user intended actions, which involves integrating user activity logs, dynamic and static user profiles based on multi-path learning, and exploiting historical user records by establishing a decaying multi-snapshot technique. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper involves interpreting and visualizing user activity logs to identify important factors critical to user attrition and retention, which suggests that it may also belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) and Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-categories. Finally, the paper discusses the potential applications of its methodology to other user intended actions, which suggests that it may also belong to the Cybersecurity (cs.CY) sub-category.
